cli-council
===========

An independent, clean-room implementation of the "LLM council" idea: ask one
question to several models, have them anonymously rank each other's answers, and
let a chairman model synthesise a final answer.

Credit / inspiration
--------------------
The three-stage council concept (first opinions -> anonymized peer review ->
chairman synthesis) is inspired by Andrej Karpathy's `llm-council`
(https://github.com/karpathy/llm-council). That project has no published
license; **no code from it was copied.** cli-council is written from scratch and
differs fundamentally in substrate: it orchestrates the official first-party
subscription CLIs you already run (Claude Code, Codex, Grok, Gemini/Antigravity) instead of
a paid HTTP API aggregator. All code here is original and MIT-licensed.

What this is NOT
----------------
- Not an API client by default. Out of the box it sends no HTTP requests to any
  model provider and needs no API keys. A voice can optionally be a token-based
  OpenAI-compatible API call, but that is strictly opt-in — declared only in your
  own local council.toml, with the key read from an environment variable at call
  time and never stored by cli-council.
- Not a credential tool. It never reads, stores, or transmits your CLI logins,
  and it stores no API keys — an opt-in token voice's key stays in your env var.
  It only invokes CLIs you authenticated yourself (through each vendor's own
  official flow) and endpoints you configured yourself.
- Not account sharing. Each user brings their own authenticated CLIs / keys on
  their own machine.
